rom the late nineteenth century, a strong modernizing trend developed within Orthodoxy based on the adoption of Hungarian national identity alongside the preservation of tradition. Modern Orthodoxy was receptive to the Hungarian language, culture, and religion. However, the attempt to integrate failed.The book traces the journey of Hungarian Jews from Emancipation to the Holocaust and seeks to understand the reasons for the Jews’ complete trust in Hungarian integrity. For instance, why did they believe until the very last moment that the Holocaust would not affect them? How could they fail to notice the impending disaster?This is the story of a community that felt rooted in the land and contributed greatly to its well-being, but was eventually rejected: the story of patriots without a homeland.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zHungary. 0aJewszHungaryxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewszHungaryxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszHungaryxIdentityxHistory. 0aOrthodox JudaismzHungaryxHistory. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / Orthodox.2bisacsh  a19th century.  a20th century.  aHistory.  aHolocaust.  aHungarian Holocaust.  aHungarian Orthodoxy.  aHungary.  aIdentity.  aJewish.  aOrthodox Judaism.1 aVardi, Shaul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076741408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023 Englishz978311131928508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE The